legacy.name: Nury Vittachi

result.text:
Oops. EPIC FAIL at the New York Times this week.

They published a long spiel implying that peace campaign groups, such as @NoColdWar, and @codepink, are paid foreign agents pushing “China’s Talking Points”. (Their “proof” is that one particular guy has donated to several of them.)

Here’s the problem. As every China reporter knows, China doesn’t have a talking points system!

It has never had one, doesn’t have one now, and, as far as I know, has never expressed an interest in introducing one.

And I should know. I live in China, work in China, and create daily journalism focused on China, alongside many China journalists.

There’s nothing like that here.

I’ve worked as a journalist in many countries around the world, including in the west and the east (I’ve written op-eds in the NYT), and there’s only one country I know in which the government issues a daily series of politicised “talking points” to journalists to push in what they write or broadcast.

That is the United States.

As for one guy donating to several anti-war groups, why imply that’s crooked? That’s the norm. You have money, you donate to the causes you believe in.

But NYT reporters (@MaraHvistendahl ,
@Fahrenthold , @lynseychutel , @ishaan_jhavs ) if you think donations to media are an issue, you do know that the US administration sets aside more than billion dollars a year for production of anti-China content. Who gets that money? Now that would be worth a New York Times investigation. But you would never do that, would you? 

Readers: whenever you see any article that alleges that a group disseminates “Chinese talking points”, there are two things you immediately know. First, those journalists don’t know China well enough to know that it doesn’t use a talking points system.

Second, this assumption strongly suggests that these NYT journalists DO follow the US administration’s talking points system!

Not a surprise.

Thomas Friedman's 1998 George Kennan interview on NATO expansion:

"I think it is the beginning of a new cold war. I think the Russians will gradually react quite adversely and it will affect their policies.

I think it is a tragic mistake. There was no reason for this whatsoever.

No one was threatening anybody else. This expansion would make the Founding Fathers of this country turn over in their graves.

Of course there is going to be a bad reaction from Russia, and then (the NATO expanders) will say that we always told you that is how the Russians are — but this is just wrong.

This has been my life, and it pains me to see it so screwed up in the end."

legacy.full_text:
